      <bioghist id="aspace_da4683bbbed8943a89e443a761a6ad5d">
         <head>Bacon Family</head>
         <p>Francis Miles Bacon (1862-1946) was born in Knoxville, Tennessee, to carpenter and lumber dealer Miles Bacon (1827-1901) and Eliza C. Colburn Bacon (1834-1923). His birth followed those of his siblings Sarah Annie Bacon (1856-1949), Lucy M. Bacon (1858-1965), and Edgar W. Bacon (1860-1875).</p>
         <p>Between 1862 and 1864, the Bacon family moved to Worcester, Massachusetts, where Florence Mable Bacon Pierce (1864-1938), Albert I. Bacon (1867-1913), and Marion E. Bacon (1869-1945) were born.</p>
         <p>Francis Bacon migrated to LaFoon, Faulk County, Dakota Territory (now South Dakota), around 1883 to homestead a farm. Florence Bacon moved to nearby Faulkton, Dakota Territory, in 1884. In 1885, she married general store owner Elmer Ellsworth Pierce (1861-1930). The couple had three children: Everett Alonzo Pierce (1892-1957), George Pierce (1902-1985), and Ellsworth Bacon Pierce (1905-1974).</p>
         <p>In 1886, Francis Bacon married Mabel "May" Louisa Sutton Bacon (1862-1907). The couple had four children: Nellie May Bacon (1887-1979), Warren Sutton Bacon (1891-1967), Ernest Miles Bacon (1893-1972), and Carolyn G. Bacon Prout (1903-1988). Following the Panic of 1893, an economic depression that persisted until 1897, the family moved to Worcester, Massachusetts. By 1930, Francis Bacon and sisters Sarah Bacon and Marion Bacon lived together on a farm in Worcester.</p>
         <p>Florence Bacon died in Atlanta, Georgia, in 1938. Francis Bacon died in Leicester, Massachusetts, in 1946.</p>
      </bioghist>
